\section*{Background \& Summary}
India's population has risen dramatically in recent decades, from 361 million in 1951 to 1,221 million at the last national census in 2011 \cite{james_indias_2011}, driving substantial environmental change \cite{tian_history_2014}. Increasing population density and a changing economy have resulted in urban development and expansion \cite{gururaja_population_2012}, while India's green revolution, initiated in the mid-1960s to achieve food security for its growing population, has resulted in the transformation of natural vegetation and rainfed agriculture to intensively managed agricultural systems \cite{scott_energy_2009,smilovic_limits_2015}. Land use/land cover change (henceforth (``land change'') has important consequences for biodiversity and the sustainability of ecosystem services upon which individuals and communities depend \cite{turner_emergence_2007}. Cumulatively, it is a major driver of global and regional environmental change \cite{foley_global_2005}, influencing the surface energy and water balance \cite{feddema_importance_2005,verburg_challenges_2011} as well as global biogeochemical cycles \cite{houghton_carbon_2012}. Since the rate and magnitude of land change varies over space and time \cite{tian_history_2014}, spatially explicit, historical datasets are necessary to accurately quantify the various environmental and societal impacts of change \cite[e.g.][]{feddema_importance_2005,verburg_challenges_2011,friedl_modis_2010,foley_solutions_2011,meiyappan_three_2012}, support planning decisions and inform predictions about the quantity and location of future change. \\

Remote sensing provides one data source for mapping land change \cite{friedl_global_2002}. Recently, \cite{roy_development_2015} developed land use/land cover maps of India for 1985, 1995 and 2005 using multitemporal satellite data from various instruments. Developing such a dataset is resource intensive and severely constrained by the quality and availability of satellite data and ground truth points that are valid for the time period considered \cite{roy_development_2015}. Moreover, the launch of the first Landsat instrument in 1972 represents the earliest time at which remote sensing could be used for land use/land cover mapping. As a result of these factors, existing work to document historical land use/land cover at global and regional scales have used various algorithms to combine contemporary land use/land cover maps from remote sensing with national and sub-national inventory data \cite{meiyappan_three_2012}. Global datasets include the HYDE database \cite{klein_goldewijk_hyde_2011} and the Earthstat global cropland and pasture dataset \cite{ramankutty_estimating_1999}. These products have a 5 arcminute $\times$ 5 arcminute spatial resolution and cover the period 10,000BC~--~2005AD and 1700--2007, respectively. In India, global datasets such as these rely on land use/land cover inventory data aggregated to state and national levels because of the difficulties in obtaining district-level data collected before 1998. As a result, they do not adequately capture the variability in the rate of change between districts, which can be considerable. For example, while the northern State of Uttar Pradesh shows a net increase in the area of agricultural land between 1956 and 2010, the area in 20\% of district units ($n=\textrm{8}$) has decreased. \\

% However, while in principle satellite data are available for the last our decades \cite{houghton_carbon_2012}, the quality and availability of data over India before the year 2000 is poor. Thus, existing work to document historical land use/land cover at global and regional scales have used various algorithms to combine contemporary land use/land cover maps from remote sensing with national and sub-national inventory data \cite{meiyappan_three_2012}. Global datasets include the HYDE database \cite{klein_goldewijk_hyde_2011} and the Earthstat global cropland and pasture dataset \cite{ramankutty_estimating_1999}. These products have a 5 arcminute $\times$ 5 arcminute spatial resolution and cover the period 10,000BC~--~2005AD and 1700--2007, respectively. In India, global datasets such as these rely on land use/land cover inventory data aggregated to state and national levels because of the difficulties in obtaining district-level data collected before 1998. As a result, they do not adequately capture the variability in the rate of change between districts, which can be considerable. For example, while the northern State of Uttar Pradesh shows a net increase in the area of agricultural land between 1956 and 2010, the area in 20\% of district units ($n=\textrm{8}$) has decreased. \\

Addressing this deficiency, \cite{tian_history_2014} developed an historical dataset for India which combines a contemporary land use/land cover map based on Resourcesat-1 satellite imagery with a commercially available dataset of district-level inventory data. The dataset has a spatial resolution of 5 arcminute $\times$ 5 arcminute and covers the period 1880--2010. Central to the approach adopted in this case as well as the global datasets mentioned previously is the assumption that the spatial distribution of historical land use/land cover is the same in relative terms as the present distribution \citep{tian_history_2014}. However, this does not adequately reproduce historical change because it fails to account for changes in the relative importance of the various factors influencing land change over time \cite{meiyappan_three_2012}. Spatially explicit land change models, which simulate future or historical land change based on statistical analysis of the quantitative relationship between the contemporary land use/land cover distribution and various socioeconomic and biophysical covariates \cite{verburg_spatial_1999}, have been suggested as an essential next step to improve historical land use/land cover reconstructions \cite{meiyappan_three_2012,tian_history_2014}. \\

%% Central to the approach adopted to create this dataset and the global datasets mentioned previously is the assumption that historical land cover distribution is the same as the present distribution \cite{tian2014}. Spatially-explicit land use change models, which simulate future or historical land use and land cover change based on the underlying biophysical and socio-economic variables, have been suggested as an essential next step to improve historical reconstructions of land use and land cover change \cite{tian2014}. Previously, \cite{ramankutty1999} rejected this approach because of a lack of sufficient ancillary datasets at global and regional scales. However, in the last decade the availability of spatially-explicit information has increased dramatically. As a result, land use change models have been used to simulate historical land cover change in Europe \cite{fuchs2015} and predict future change in Europe \cite{verburg2009} and Africa \cite{schaldach2011}. \\

This paper presents a new dataset showing historical land change in India between 1960--2010. It uses the HIstoric Land Dynamics Assessment (HILDA) land change model \cite{fuchs_high-resolution_2013,fuchs_gross_2015} to combine district-level inventory data with a state of the art high-resolution land use/land cover product for the year 2005 \cite{roy_development_2015}. The resulting dataset, which has a spatial resolution of 100m $\times$ 100m and provides a land use/land cover map for each year of the study period, shows the evolution of agriculture, forest, grassland, shrubland, wasteland, barren land and urban areas. It is the first publicly available, spatially explicit dataset derived from district-level inventory data showing land change in India during the second half the twentieth century. \\
