\subsection*{Land change modelling procedure}

%% Statistical analysis and the spatial allocation of land use/land cover change was performed in the R environment using the \textit{lulcc} software package developed in Chapter 2. 
Random forest, a non-parametric ensemble learning method that is robust against overfitting and efficiently handles datasets with a large number of input variables \cite{breiman_random_2001,svetnik_random_2003}, was used to fit models of the spatial distribution of land use/land cover in 2005 with the biophysical and socio-economic predictor variables. The random forest algorithm constructs multiple classification trees using different bootstrap samples of the data \cite{breiman_random_2001}, splitting tree nodes using the best split among a random selection of variables \cite{breiman_random_2001,liaw_classification_2002}. For regression tasks the results from individual trees are combined by taking the mean prediction. The statistical analysis was performed on a stratified random subset containing 1000 pixels from each land use/land cover class. This subset was further divided into training and test sets according to a 70:30 ratio. All models (agriculture, forest, grassland, shrubland, wasteland, urban) were trained and tested on the same data partitions. A statistical model was not required for barren land because, as the land use/land cover class with the lowest socioeconomic value, it is automatically assigned to unallocated pixels once the other classes have been modelled. \\

% A random sample of 1e6 cells (approximately Y\% of the total) were used for statistical analysis. The selected cells were a minimum distance from each other in order to reduce the influence of spatial autocorrelation on the analysis \cite{verburg_modeling_2002}. 

The HILDA model was applied to each district using demand scenarios constructed from the inventory data. Seven land use/land cover types were modelled in the following order: urban land, cropland, grassland, shrubland, wasteland and barren land. Water and snow and ice classes were included in the simulation but assumed to be constant over the study period. The resulting district-level land use/land cover maps were combined to generate an historical land change dataset for the entire Indian subcontinent. \\

